Meet the Ukrainian unit tasked with finding fallen soldiers…

The death toll of the war in Ukraine is difficult to know for certain. Neither side publicizes their own numbers of casualties or deaths, but in April U.S. estimates were made public after a trove of Pentagon documents leaked on Discord. The numbers, now months old, are staggering. 

The U.S. estimated that Russia has sustained up to 223,000 casualties as of February, including up to 43,000 Russian soldiers killed in action – according to a New York Times review of the documents. The documents also included U.S. estimates for Ukraine: up to 131,000 casualties, including 17,500 Ukrainian soldiers killed in action. 

Our team travelled Eastern Ukraine to try and get sense of the true death toll – the heavy cost of war – through the eyes of a unit responsible for recovering bodies left on the battlefield.
.
.
.
w/ Dan Gallo, Anastasiia Parafeniuk, Andy Viganas, Cheryll Simpson, & Maura Murphy

New York City’s Mayor says they’re in the midst of a humanitarian crisis and unable to house the growing number of asylum seekers. Ukrainian officials thought their pilots would be training on American-made F-16s by now, but it hasn’t happened yet. 

A spokesperson with Ukraine’s Air Force says the first group of pilots will begin training in Denmark, but as of Monday - they didn’t have an official start date. 
 
On Friday, the US reiterated that Ukraine will get F16s, as soon as training is complete — but the training might not be completed before summer 2024, according to a U.S. official who spoke to NBC News. 

US military analysts tell us the delays are already hampering Ukraine’s counteroffensive. 

We take you to the skies for an up close look at the fighter jet everyone’s talking about. 

Thursday’s @topstorynbc report — w/ Kevin Urgiles and Alejandro Basalo

We were with a group of journalists taken by the Israeli government to see Kibbutz Be’eri. 

It almost looks like a tornado ripped through here, but people did this to other people. 

Homes charred. 

Roofs collapsed. 

Piles of rubble. 

Spent rounds scattered in the grass. 

Bullet holes through the windows. 

This kibbutz was home to roughly 1,000 people. More than 100 people were massacred on October 7th, according to the Israeli government. 
.
.
.
#israel #gaza #israelgazawar #news #newsupdate #nbcnews

The horrors of war on display — on both sides of the Israel Gaza border. 

In Israel, forensic teams are using DNA to identify victims of Hamas’ terror attack because many were so brutally tortured — their bodies are unrecognizable. 

In Gaza, entire families are being wiped out by Israeli airstrikes — bodies, marked with numbers instead of names, buried in mass graves as health officials struggle to keep up with the growing number of dead. 

Our @topstorynbc report. 
.

wrapping up a month covering the Israel-Hamas War … one journalist rant about access before I head home for a bit: 

If you’re wondering why more foreign journalists aren’t reporting from inside of Gaza — it’s not for lack of effort. We have to have permission to enter countries we’re not citizens of. We can’t go into Gaza without permission from border authorities: in this case that’s Israel or Egypt and Hamas.

Israel’s border crossing to Gaza has been closed since Oct 7. 

Egypt only recently opened theirs to allow aid in and injured Palestinians/foreign nationals out. 

NBC has a phenomenal team in Gaza risking their own safety and working around the clock to get us images from the ground, but foreign journalists should be allowed inside Gaza — not just on tightly controlled embeds with the IDF.
